@node Purpose 

  -=> Purpose of S(uper) 60 II :

      This tool was made in a few time to bridge a gap in the amount of 
softwares that exists for my Amiga : there wasn't one nice, system 
friendly prog that was able to switch from 60Hz to 50Hz or from 50Hz to 
60Hz .

So I decided to do S60 II of my own . ( I know it is easy to code BUT ) 

      60 Hz mode is really useful for people who have NTSC games (DOS) on
their Hard Disks and a PAL Amiga and want to play in a fullscreen mode .
So they load S60 II, select 60Hz ( the screen should stretch ) and load 
their games . They can also make a project icon or put it in the startup-
sequence of their games .


For instance, try an old game in 60Hz : Great Courts 2      

      60 Hz mode increases the speed of some games like Great Courts 2 
or Stunt Car Racer

      Besides, S60 can also decrease the sparkling of interlaced screen,
like 640*512 on my TV screen . Try to play klondike III using S60 ...

                           @{" Why not restart now ??? " link Main}  


@endnode  



@node Use 
 
  -=> Hey how should I use that ugly tool ?? :

    * First you must register you by sending me 1000 $ .
      Then you will get the full working version .
      Ho Ho Ho I think I miss something because this is the full
      working version .
      
      Stop joking .
      
    * Easy to use ... Easy to wear ...
      Simply use the right mouse button ( or space bar ) to toggle between
      the modes and the left one ( or Esc )to exit when your choice is done .
       
      You can also read the instructions in the window      

      Now you NEEDN'T load S60 II from a project icon . 
      
      I suggest you to use Addtools 1.11 or the great Tools Daemon by 
      Nico François and put S60 II in the menus .


    * V0.80 comes with its lots of options ; I will try to explain them 
      as shortly as possible

      - First possibility : you load it from a WB icon
            
            Alone S60 II notices it's in a WB and open a window, 
            you've just to read what's in it
      
      - Second ( & Last ) possibility : you load it in a CLI

            Alone it also notices it's living in a CLI .
            How lucky it is ... isn't it ??????
            Nevertheless, if you haven't typed anything, it writes how to 
            use it .
            
            blablabla blablabla
 
           THE OPTIONS :

                 -60  =>   it puts on the @{" 60Hz mode " system "S60II_1.03 -60"} of your Amiga 
                      
                 -50  =>   it (blablabla) @{" 50Hz mode " system "S60II_1.03 -50"} (blablabla)  


                 -w   =>   it opens the same window as if it was in a @{" WB " system "S60II_1.03 -w"}
                           ( Trick : use  Run S60 if you want it to give   
                             you the control back in the CLI without
                             opening a new one )

                 -W   =>   it opens another window, a  @{" S T R A N G E " system "S60II_1.03 -W"} one
                           indeed, you can only swap between the modes 
                           with the HELP key and quit with DEL .
                           So it enables you to let him make his way, 
                           alone in your environment ; then you can swap
                           whenever you want, wherever you want .
                           ( Trick : in DOpus, if you wanna swap, click 
                             first on the "?", in the right corner )
                           ( I'm looking for a better key than HELP... )

                 -(Here you have to try all the other (capital) letters if 
                   you wanna discover a 100% useless, but sweet, option)      
                 
                      =>    nice, isn't it ?


    * I think you 've learnt enough about S60 II . @{" Goodnight " link Main} .


@endnode    


@node Add

  -=> Something to add ? :

  S60 II Version 1.03 written 100 % (200 %) in ASM .

  It doesn't use much CPU time, which is quite a good thing !

  It uses system font : so beware of the fonts you're using if it 
  looks ugly . ( I use Pearl 8 )
  
  Use Magic WB palette if you want the icon to look nice !!!!


  Future plans are :
                         - Use of gadtools.library (Soon)
                         - Reset resident
                         - ??????    


  This tools has been successfully tested on :

         -    A4000 68EC030  2 Mo Chip  8 Mo Fastram
         -    A4000 68040    2 Mo Chip 12 Mo Fastram Retina (2 Monitors)
         -    A1200 68EC020  2 Mo Chip
         -    A1200 68030/50 2 Mo Chip  4 Mo Fastram
               
    
  It also works on A500 with a super fat Agnus
  
  
  /\/ Have fµn and spread this třřl as lřng as yřu want tř ... /\/


